(301, 'jnews_instagram_widget_cache', 'a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:8:\"username\";s:6:\"natgeo\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583402613;s:4:\"feed\";a:9:{i:0;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257994859011099335\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583393987;s:4:\"like\";i:54189;s:7:\"comment\";i:138;s:7:\"caption\";s:555:\"Photo by  nataliekeyssar   Advances in DNA technology may help unlock cold cases from Guatemala s civil war  creating hope for families who have spent years wondering what became of their disappeared loved ones  Rosalina Tuyuc  human rights activist and founder of Conavigua  the national association of Guatemalan widows  counts a husband and father among the missing  She took her family to visit the memorial she helped construct at the site of several mass graves  Read more about this history in Nina Strochlic s article at the link in Nat Geo s bio \";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9WAlxkA8rH/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:247:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/fr/e15/s1080x1080/89263406_645386529612285_7513250946606248228_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=6B828lUtUXMAX9ppZk_&oh=d7504da470eccc47dcbc47f5f8ecef15&oe=5E98EC78\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:258:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e15/c180.0.720.720a/s640x640/89263406_645386529612285_7513250946606248228_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=6B828lUtUXMAX9ppZk_&oh=630bb4c380a6f66a515a08c982888635&oe=5E9767EF\";}}i:1;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257871320408910278\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583379261;s:4:\"like\";i:223667;s:7:\"comment\";i:420;s:7:\"caption\";s:945:\"Photo by  beverlyjoubert   Just recently  dereckjoubert and I found ourselves sitting in the stillness of the deepening dusk in the Masaai Mara reserve and listening to the calls of lions in the distance  It   s a sound that has always brought us joy   but more and more  it now evokes an unsettling sense of anxiety too  We listen and we imagine a time  not that long ago  when these unmistakable low-pitched calls would have resonated all across the African continent  And we feel keenly aware that the distant roars we hear now are those of the dwindling survivors    representatives of the 20 000 or so lions that have managed to cling to existence despite the daunting convergence of threats big cats face in a world shaped by humans  As their calls dissolve with the light  we also find ourselves projecting forward into an uncertain future   determined to fight to ensure that future is not silent   thisismytrophy  bigcats  causeanuproar\";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9VkgDRg-nG/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:248:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/fr/e15/s1080x1080/88203698_2842608532464105_5824450342041871450_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=dEa-rPY0DTIAX9l3gJT&oh=57873167a5d10e8492c940eb9487c173&oe=5E931A51\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:250:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e15/c236.0.607.607a/88203698_2842608532464105_5824450342041871450_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=dEa-rPY0DTIAX9l3gJT&oh=6eb0759a5be21c224f311e4a5d154c57&oe=5E929196\";}}i:2;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257810172365001232\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583371971;s:4:\"like\";i:172656;s:7:\"comment\";i:447;s:7:\"caption\";s:276:\"Photo by Muhammed Muheisen  mmuheisen   Syrian refugees play in a tent settlement in Jordan  For more photos and videos of the refugee crisis  follow me  mmuheisen  mmuheisenpublic  For more on how to get involved  follow  everydayrefugees   muhammedmuheisen  everydayrefugees\";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9VWmOuFFIQ/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:245:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/fr/e15/s1080x1080/88922472_534651314093132_53662061777753894_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=MERgHDyDGSQAX_RrRRU&oh=2c247a78b6903470a6f85219cd037244&oe=5E8F0029\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:255:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e15/c63.0.954.954a/s640x640/88922472_534651314093132_53662061777753894_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=MERgHDyDGSQAX_RrRRU&oh=941d320971a9a642b39908e543b92159&oe=5E93E471\";}}i:3;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257752268437649392\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583365079;s:4:\"like\";i:115184;s:7:\"comment\";i:539;s:7:\"caption\";s:376:\"Video by  joelsartore   An endangered female Visayan hornbill plays with a piece of watermelon during a photo shoot at Negros Forest Park in the Philippines  As a small  forest-dwelling hornbill  this species is most easily located in the wild by voice  To see a still shot of this beautiful bird follow me  joelsartore   hornbill  colorful  watermelon  PhotoArk  savetogether\";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9VJbnfDvfw/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:233:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/88905136_871072710001775_4023515496085130358_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=wYGMfGMUjiQAX98VTqn&oh=aa60ff304135ee48f0d4ff97b1356042&oe=5E635273\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:249:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/c157.0.405.405a/88905136_871072710001775_4023515496085130358_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=wYGMfGMUjiQAX98VTqn&oh=41249e6e59b8e5e07b140763a997bcc2&oe=5E6336BB\";}}i:4;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257631021041108208\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583350611;s:4:\"like\";i:348615;s:7:\"comment\";i:1004;s:7:\"caption\";s:706:\"Photo by Stephen Alvarez  salvarezphoto   The Blythe geoglyphs are the most famous of the hundreds of geoglyphs in the desert of Southern California and southwestern Arizona  Their scale is immense  The large figure in this group of two is over 170 feet  50 meters  from fingertip to fingertip  First noticed from the air in the 1930s  these figures have suffered from all-terrain vehicle traffic  They are now fenced to keep them safe  The images were created by Native Americans who removed stones from the desert floor  revealing lighter colored soil underneath  Theses were photographed as part of a project for my nonprofit  ancientartarchive  follow me  salvarezphoto and  ancientartarchive for more \";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9Ut3PDDsTw/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:234:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/89069604_1557045377796731_1953165130177443940_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=4GiQmWv077MAX8C4bQF&oh=fa29f4d5a29d89f4f2789b3273d28f12&oe=5E944389\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:250:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/sh0.08/e35/s640x640/89069604_1557045377796731_1953165130177443940_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=4GiQmWv077MAX8C4bQF&oh=e6d800cedab055c3f236e01c8dea25b7&oe=5E99D433\";}}i:5;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257511540436349771\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583336389;s:4:\"like\";i:119573;s:7:\"comment\";i:638;s:7:\"caption\";s:1068:\"Video by  amivitale   Beloved orphaned elephants Shaba  Pokot  and Mpala have been successfully reintroduced to the wild by the team at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary   r e s c u e   Shaba had been the matriarch of the herd of orphaned elephants since  r e s c u e opened in 2016  She took care of the newly arrived orphans  making sure they were protected and felt nurtured when they were vulnerable and weak  Pokot and Mpala were victims of the drought  Pokot was the fun-loving lone bull that always liked to lag behind the herd  while female Mpala was one of the team  always in the middle of playful antics  Now they are back in the wild where they belong  All three are doing exceptionally well and immediately integrated into one of the wild herds at the Sera Wildlife Conservancy in northern Kenya  Follow  amivitale and  r e s c u e to get involved and support this crucial work   conservationorg  kenyawildlifeservice  nrt kenya  sandiegozoo  tusk org  thephotosociety  natgeoimagecollection  photography for good  protectelephants  elephants  stoppoaching  kenya\";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9USskEDbNL/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:233:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/88288759_496253147704081_7655561905903490027_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=MaSwS0KPxHIAX8Clmvb&oh=d717013207a154fc0a82f377719a3f6e&oe=5E638556\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:249:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/c157.0.406.406a/88288759_496253147704081_7655561905903490027_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=MaSwS0KPxHIAX8Clmvb&oh=b1d1a2bed43f40806abfc02d93cebae0&oe=5E62EB71\";}}i:6;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257477739463124737\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583332339;s:4:\"like\";i:221407;s:7:\"comment\";i:363;s:7:\"caption\";s:170:\"Photo by David Chancellor  chancellordavid   A herder gathers his livestock at sunset  in the Simien Mountains  Ethiopia  To see more follow me  chancellordavid  ethiopia\";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9ULAsdDScB/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:244:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/88268929_241729516857441_5691391244823033430_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=CqOhjO2HQ9YAX_TCAqN&oh=74f23ca2e46a468afac2f895b7128896&oe=5E97F8FD\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:267:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/sh0.08/e35/c140.0.1159.1159a/s640x640/88268929_241729516857441_5691391244823033430_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=CqOhjO2HQ9YAX_TCAqN&oh=84f42dd274259d0cb09cf89f313d9182&oe=5E984CD1\";}}i:7;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257360954286076687\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583318417;s:4:\"like\";i:187002;s:7:\"comment\";i:502;s:7:\"caption\";s:1204:\"Photo by  robertclarkphoto   One of the great aspects of working for  natgeo is that you have the opportunity to work with some of the best editors in the industry  like Kurt Mutchler  who was the photo editor assigned to the  New Science of Pain  article in the January issue   Usually  the photographer is given a large amount of information to digest and to research  But when it comes to Kurt  most of the visual ideas are already thought-out   my job is to try and add something interesting that will make people stop on the image and delve into the caption  Kurt and I have worked on over twenty stories together  He s selected me because of my experience as a photojournalist as well as being able use studio and location lighting   When I met Vitaly Napadow  a neuroscientist at Harvard Medical School and Massachusetts General Hospital who studies how the brain perceives pain  I had an idea straight away  One of the methods he uses is electroencephalography to track the brain wave patterns of patients who suffer from chronic lower back pain  I wanted to show the headset for this process  and he was kind enough to model it for me  above   Check out Nat Geo s Instagram Story today for more \";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9TwdPyDvMP/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:245:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/p1080x1080/89041380_2699790946943979_6269468785818186102_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=1lRFzAFEXowAX-FjFCN&oh=aa8dbc561a999a100ad2d0d05bef79ad&oe=5E984AFA\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:268:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/sh0.08/e35/c0.179.1440.1440a/s640x640/89041380_2699790946943979_6269468785818186102_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=1lRFzAFEXowAX-FjFCN&oh=fa5f9cb365307bfdb22f98826088a217&oe=5E9925BA\";}}i:8;a:7:{s:2:\"id\";s:19:\"2257148192846889193\";s:4:\"time\";i:1583293054;s:4:\"like\";i:226777;s:7:\"comment\";i:640;s:7:\"caption\";s:1128:\"Photo by  anandavarma   When it comes to appreciating  wildlife   plants tend to get less attention than animals  This particular plant deserves special recognition for the fact that it eats animals for lunch  This is an inch-long fragment of a carnivorous aquatic plant called a bladderwort  Utricularia gibba   Those bulbous structures are the    bladders    that the plant uses to trap tiny aquatic invertebrates  The plant evolved this strategy in order to survive in nutrient-poor water  Look for the pairs of tiny hairs that look like whiskers on the bladders  These act as triggers  causing the bladders to suction up whatever critter passes by  I took this photo while on expedition with the  intotheokavango team on their annual survey of the Okavango Delta   These images and videos are part of my Invisible Wonders project  I love how photography can reveal the lives of secretive animals  magnify details that are too small to notice  and speed up or slow down processes that are barely perceptible to our naked eye  Capturing these hidden details reminds me there is always more to see when you pay close attention \";s:4:\"link\";s:30:\"//instagram.com/p/B9TAFKQDcDp/\";s:6:\"images\";a:2:{s:7:\"display\";s:244:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/89259345_2841484795933919_324607587105290186_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=Im25VjvIz4oAX-kYXDZ&oh=92b94b63dcc844cc367bdb67dec9903f&oe=5E8E34B7\";s:9:\"thumbnail\";s:249:\"https://instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/sh0.08/e35/s640x640/89259345_2841484795933919_324607587105290186_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsgn3-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=1&_nc_ohc=Im25VjvIz4oAX-kYXDZ&oh=7446c70e0ceecc3caba63a2286008716&oe=5E921600\";}}}}}', 'yes'),
